In TypeScript, you can use the "as" operator to tell the type system that you know the type of a value, even if it is not statically known. Here's an example:

const myValue: string | number = getValue();

// Tell the type system that you know the type of `myValue` is a string:
const myStringValue = myValue as string;

// You can now use `myStringValue` as a string without any type errors:
console.log(myStringValue.toUpperCase());

In this example, `myValue` is of type `string | number`, but you know that it will only have the type `string`. The "as" operator allows you to tell the type system that you know this to be true, and to treat `myValue` as a string. This can be useful when you have a value whose type cannot be determined statically, but you know its type at runtime.

Here is a sample C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    std::string word;
    int count = 0;
    std::ifstream file("file.txt");
    if (file.is_open()) {
        while (file.good()) {
            std::string line;
            getline(file, line);
            if (line.find(word) != std::string::npos) {
                count++;
            }
        }
    } else {
        std::cout << "Unable to open file" << std::endl;
    }
    std::cout << "Number of occurrences of " << word << ": " << count << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```
